00:26:55.400 --> 00:27:00.599
for someone who's getting into dashboards, what are tips and tricks that you wish you knew

00:27:00.599 --> 00:27:05.719
when you started? Like, if you have evolved your dashboarding over the years, what are some things

00:27:05.719 --> 00:27:09.079
that maybe you did wrong when you first started and you wish you'd done better?

00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:15.160
Yeah. So, that's a great question. And Carlos will have some great insights here too,

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:21.160
because he's the dashboard king now. And he's been writing mostly in Python dash.

00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:25.560
And I, of course, came from an R background. So, that's what I love about Connect too. It's

00:27:25.560 --> 00:27:32.760
platform independent, right? You can use Python, you can use R. So, it doesn't matter with R Shiny.

00:27:32.760 --> 00:27:39.719
But specifically to dashboards, the first thing I would do when I was asked to create a dashboard

00:27:39.719 --> 00:27:46.280
is I would step back for a minute and I would get out a piece of paper or a whiteboard,

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:51.319
and I would try to draw it out visually. What do I want? And what does the stakeholder want? You

00:27:51.319 --> 00:27:55.239
got to get to the stakeholder. What are you trying to communicate to them? And often,

00:27:55.239 --> 00:27:59.959
the stakeholder doesn't always know what they want. So, it's your job to interpret what they're

00:27:59.959 --> 00:28:02.920
saying. And are you going to do a graph? Are you going to do a map? Are you going to do

00:28:03.959 --> 00:28:11.400
info boxes? And then how can you communicate? Then the second question is, okay, what's the

00:28:11.400 --> 00:28:17.079
data source going to be? And how am I going to access the data, right? And you need to design

00:28:17.079 --> 00:28:23.560
that in your head and keep that process separate from the dashboard. So, I always recommend write

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:29.319
a... I mean, I'm speaking in the R world, but Python script or R Markdown, write a Markdown

00:28:29.319 --> 00:28:36.199
file that's going to generate and do all of your data processing first. Summarize it to create a

00:28:36.760 --> 00:28:44.439
CSV or Excel file or whatever, you know, or push it to an intermediate database. And then you have

00:28:44.439 --> 00:28:49.319
your dashboard file, which is your dashboard, which is going to read from that intermediate

00:28:49.319 --> 00:29:00.680
file, okay, and serve up the data. So, to be more specific, doing that will allow you to separate

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:06.920
the data generation process from the dashboard so that the dashboard can run independently

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:13.640
when you update data, right? And we can get into all kinds of architecture discussions on that.

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:14.839
But...

00:29:14.957 --> 00:29:19.317
and we can get into all kinds of architecture discussions on that,

00:29:19.317 --> 00:29:23.117
but it's important because your needs are going to change,

00:29:23.117 --> 00:29:25.877
the data is going to change, and you're going to,

00:29:25.877 --> 00:29:27.997
if you do something really well the first time,

00:29:27.997 --> 00:29:29.437
someone's going to come to you and say,

00:29:29.437 --> 00:29:31.197
hey, can you update this?

00:29:31.197 --> 00:29:32.997
And if you don't make it easy to update,

00:29:32.997 --> 00:29:34.877
then that's going to be a challenge.

00:29:34.877 --> 00:29:38.317
So I always advocate separating the data process from that.

00:29:38.317 --> 00:29:40.676
Then the other pieces on the visual design,

00:29:41.756 --> 00:29:43.237
pick the right architecture,

00:29:43.237 --> 00:29:47.157
and then the page structure and keep your pages simple.

00:29:47.157 --> 00:29:48.837
Like I said, the Three-Click Rule,

00:29:49.797 --> 00:29:54.117
try to use the right tool for the right thing.

00:29:54.117 --> 00:29:57.916
And if you're trying to create like data-driven drill downs,

00:29:57.916 --> 00:30:01.477
like you might see in Power BI and you have Power BI,

00:30:01.477 --> 00:30:03.396
you might want to use Power BI,

00:30:03.396 --> 00:30:06.837
but most people don't need that.

00:30:06.837 --> 00:30:09.317
And if you're communicating for executives,

00:30:09.317 --> 00:30:10.396
you want to be able,

00:30:10.437 --> 00:30:12.157
they need to be able to go to the page

00:30:12.157 --> 00:30:15.076
and they need to see it and gather information

00:30:15.076 --> 00:30:20.077
from visual cues, whether it's graphics or info boxes.

00:30:20.196 --> 00:30:23.637
So for example, you could put an info box up there.

00:30:23.637 --> 00:30:26.876
When I read income in, if income were positive,

00:30:26.876 --> 00:30:29.037
I would make it green.

00:30:29.037 --> 00:30:31.997
If income were negative, I might make it red

00:30:31.997 --> 00:30:33.796
and put the change in there, right?

00:30:33.796 --> 00:30:35.916
So now the user can come in and quickly see,

00:30:35.916 --> 00:30:39.037
oh, my income's down, my loan growth is up,

00:30:39.077 --> 00:30:42.236
my this, you know, all of those different pieces.

00:30:42.236 --> 00:30:44.796
And they can gather that information

00:30:44.796 --> 00:30:48.717
with visual information very quickly in that case.

00:30:48.717 --> 00:30:52.677
So yeah, Carlos, do you want to talk some more

00:30:52.677 --> 00:30:54.077
about dashboards that you've learned?

00:30:54.077 --> 00:30:58.277
You've recently deployed quite a few of them, so.

00:30:58.277 --> 00:31:01.397
Yeah, so like I mentioned, in terms of dashboards,

00:31:01.397 --> 00:31:04.757
I also started and I wish some of the things

00:31:04.757 --> 00:31:07.556
that I wish I would have known more in the beginning

00:31:07.556 --> 00:31:10.596
was the first one to emphasize is that modularity.

00:31:10.596 --> 00:31:14.196
Like it's a lot of, no matter how great you build it,

00:31:14.196 --> 00:31:16.117
whenever the first version goes out,

00:31:16.117 --> 00:31:19.037
you are going to get feedback on changing things.

00:31:19.037 --> 00:31:22.677
So make sure all the code is modular,

00:31:22.677 --> 00:31:26.957
you can move things around because there are some things

00:31:26.957 --> 00:31:28.636
that usually the user would say,

00:31:28.636 --> 00:31:30.317
oh, I would like to move this,

00:31:30.317 --> 00:31:34.317
and it's a big change.

00:31:34.317 --> 00:31:37.957
Or then another one, it's that they would think it's small,

00:31:37.957 --> 00:31:38.876
it's actually big.

00:31:38.876 --> 00:31:41.996
So modularizing is something that I really put

00:31:41.996 --> 00:31:43.516
a lot of emphasis in.

00:31:43.516 --> 00:31:46.557
Then the other thing when I start doing these dashboards

00:31:46.557 --> 00:31:49.156
is I think a lot about the use case

00:31:49.156 --> 00:31:51.957
and who my target audience is.

00:31:51.957 --> 00:31:53.876
Just like Jason mentioned,

00:31:53.876 --> 00:31:57.037
if you're going to build something for an executive,

00:31:57.037 --> 00:32:00.516
you only have 30 seconds to read all the information

00:32:00.516 --> 00:32:01.557
that you have on.

00:32:01.557 --> 00:32:03.076
But if you're going to build something more

00:32:03.076 --> 00:32:04.197
for like an analyst,

00:32:04.197 --> 00:32:07.477
you can actually put more detailed information

00:32:07.477 --> 00:32:11.516
because an analyst might stay in the dashboard more

00:32:11.516 --> 00:32:13.716
and do more investigation.

00:32:13.716 --> 00:32:16.876
So that's how I like to preface my things.

00:32:16.876 --> 00:32:21.876
And then also one tip that Jason has told me

00:32:21.876 --> 00:32:23.917
and I mentioned a few times, that three-click rule.

00:32:23.917 --> 00:32:25.716
If people need to click a lot,

00:32:25.716 --> 00:32:30.716
then you won't be able to make them stay.

00:32:30.716 --> 00:32:33.716
And then also some of the tips I've seen online

00:32:33.716 --> 00:32:35.716
is I like drill downs,

00:32:35.716 --> 00:32:38.796
but drill downs by clicking on different things.

00:32:38.796 --> 00:32:42.837
So if you have a KPI at the highest level of aggregation,

00:32:42.837 --> 00:32:44.436
let's just say you have a customer

00:32:44.436 --> 00:32:46.356
and then you click on it and you see

00:32:46.356 --> 00:32:48.317
all the different things that they have underneath

00:32:48.317 --> 00:32:49.356
and then you click again.

00:32:49.356 --> 00:32:52.317
And so that level,

00:32:52.317 --> 00:32:56.397
going down on that level of aggregation on one same page,

00:32:56.397 --> 00:33:01.397
it's something that I've seen stakeholders really like

00:33:01.516 --> 00:33:05.716
just that way they can see what they need to see.

00:33:05.716 --> 00:33:07.076
If they have a question about it,

00:33:07.076 --> 00:33:10.436
they can start a investigation a little bit more.

00:33:10.436 --> 00:33:14.596
And then touching a little bit more on AI piece,

00:33:14.596 --> 00:33:18.957
I would say in this case, we use GitHub Copilot,

00:33:18.957 --> 00:33:22.757
but any AI tool that you would like to leverage,

00:33:22.757 --> 00:33:26.076
I would say start playing with it a little bit

00:33:26.757 --> 00:33:29.917
and start using one thing that changed completely

00:33:29.917 --> 00:33:32.036
my workflow was the different skills

00:33:32.036 --> 00:33:34.796
that you can put in the different AIs.

00:33:34.796 --> 00:33:38.277
That way the AI start building the code

00:33:38.277 --> 00:33:39.756
just as you would like it.

00:33:39.756 --> 00:33:43.437
Because some of the problems that I've had

00:33:43.437 --> 00:33:46.557
is sometimes I need a simple function or something

00:33:46.557 --> 00:33:49.557
and the AI writes something super complicated

00:33:49.557 --> 00:33:51.877
that I truly don't understand.

00:33:51.877 --> 00:33:54.796
So just trying to make those markdown files

00:33:54.796 --> 00:33:56.877
on how you like different things,

00:33:56.877 --> 00:33:59.117
I would say would be a good thing.

00:33:59.117 --> 00:34:00.837
And then the finish off,

00:34:00.837 --> 00:34:05.316
it would be, I would investigate different libraries

00:34:05.316 --> 00:34:07.076
that you have, just like PositConnect.

00:34:07.076 --> 00:34:09.196
That is one of the good things about PositConnect.

00:34:09.196 --> 00:34:11.597
It's not only Shiny, but you have R,

00:34:11.597 --> 00:34:13.597
