00:36:46.117 --> 00:36:47.356
You can see all these,

00:36:47.756 --> 00:36:51.236
look at all these categories of loans that I can do.

00:36:51.236 --> 00:36:52.557
Look at all this that I can do.

00:36:52.557 --> 00:36:54.157
Look at all that.

00:36:54.157 --> 00:36:58.636
Well, that's forcing the user to make the decision

00:36:58.636 --> 00:37:01.157
and to go in and try to click at it.

00:37:01.157 --> 00:37:03.157
And they're gonna get it wrong.

00:37:03.157 --> 00:37:04.356
It's gonna be slow.

00:37:04.356 --> 00:37:07.157
It's not gonna be performant, okay?

00:37:07.157 --> 00:37:11.316
And so, you know, this is where the conversations

00:37:11.316 --> 00:37:14.117
with the stakeholders like, what would you like to see?

00:37:14.117 --> 00:37:15.196
What are you getting at?

00:37:15.957 --> 00:37:20.557
What really is the key information that you are looking for?

00:37:20.557 --> 00:37:22.796
And this is where your job as a data scientist

00:37:22.796 --> 00:37:27.356
is to interpret that and figure out, well, okay,

00:37:27.356 --> 00:37:32.356
how can I display all of this information in a useful way?

00:37:32.677 --> 00:37:36.957
And how can I get it and make it intelligible?

00:37:36.957 --> 00:37:40.076
And so that's why like, instead of say,

00:37:40.076 --> 00:37:43.957
having a selector for each individual loan category

00:37:43.957 --> 00:37:47.397
on the same page, you know, I just created multiple pages.

00:37:47.397 --> 00:37:49.397
So it was easy to just click on the header

00:37:49.397 --> 00:37:51.277
at the top of the different categories

00:37:51.277 --> 00:37:53.756
and everybody saw the same page.

00:37:53.756 --> 00:37:56.477
They had the same information on each page,

00:37:56.477 --> 00:38:01.477
but it was, you know, different categories.

00:38:02.556 --> 00:38:05.157
So it made it performant, responsive,

00:38:05.157 --> 00:38:08.076
and they could see like the waterfall chart, for example.

00:38:08.076 --> 00:38:10.756
I love waterfalls in finance, but, you know,

00:38:10.756 --> 00:38:15.037
the waterfall charts would show you where your, you know,

00:38:15.037 --> 00:38:17.436
your portfolio's going and any risks there.

00:38:17.436 --> 00:38:19.837
And the other thing I would do that I used to do

00:38:19.837 --> 00:38:22.037
is pre-populate certain fields, right?

00:38:22.037 --> 00:38:23.676
With default information,

00:38:23.676 --> 00:38:26.636
if you're using selectors or date variables.

00:38:26.636 --> 00:38:30.037
So if they're pre-populated to maybe the current year

00:38:30.037 --> 00:38:31.957
or the last 12 months,

00:38:31.957 --> 00:38:34.516
whatever you think the stakeholder's looking for,

00:38:34.516 --> 00:38:36.397
you know, that still allows someone to go in

00:38:36.397 --> 00:38:38.717
and select and change and maybe see two years,

00:38:38.717 --> 00:38:40.676
but having it pre-populated,

00:38:40.676 --> 00:38:43.316
it's just one less click they have to do.

00:38:43.316 --> 00:38:48.316
And so those are a few of my tricks and tips there.

00:38:48.797 --> 00:38:50.556
And Carlos, you're closer to that.

00:38:50.556 --> 00:38:53.717
Do you have any questions, any thoughts there?

00:38:53.717 --> 00:38:55.597
No, yeah, great question.

00:38:55.597 --> 00:38:58.717
I've always actually said that building the dashboard

00:38:58.717 --> 00:38:59.876
is the easiest part.

00:38:59.876 --> 00:39:02.676
Knowing what the user actually wants to see

00:39:02.676 --> 00:39:05.837
and how to present it is the most complicated.

00:39:05.837 --> 00:39:07.917
So I guess it comes down,

00:39:07.917 --> 00:39:10.316
like Jason mentioned in the beginning,

00:39:10.316 --> 00:39:12.597
sometimes the stakeholder,

00:39:12.597 --> 00:39:15.316
because I don't know in your guys' expertise,

00:39:15.316 --> 00:39:17.597
but I've never had a stakeholder say exactly,

00:39:17.597 --> 00:39:19.277
I want to see this, this, this, and that.

00:39:19.277 --> 00:39:22.797
It's like, you need to kind of like get it out of him

00:39:22.797 --> 00:39:25.597
and to see, connect what the problem,

00:39:25.597 --> 00:39:28.277
because a stakeholder comes to you with a problem,

00:39:28.277 --> 00:39:31.636
but he doesn't know what data or where that data is.

00:39:31.636 --> 00:39:35.556
So your job as a data scientist is to kind of,

00:39:36.237 --> 00:39:37.316
like Jason said, filter that out

00:39:37.316 --> 00:39:40.037
and to see what KPIs he wants to see

00:39:40.037 --> 00:39:41.516
or what are those changes.

00:39:41.516 --> 00:39:43.717
So I would put a lot of emphasis

00:39:43.717 --> 00:39:47.357
in meeting with the stakeholder in the beginning.

00:39:47.357 --> 00:39:51.636
Don't write any code because if you write something,

00:39:51.636 --> 00:39:53.556
you're gonna have to redo it again.

00:39:53.556 --> 00:39:58.556
So I would say that those first stakeholder meetings

00:39:58.636 --> 00:40:00.037
on what you would like to see,

00:40:00.037 --> 00:40:02.957
present him with ideas way before

00:40:02.957 --> 00:40:04.676
even writing a single line of code

00:40:04.676 --> 00:40:07.157
will be the most important one.

00:40:07.157 --> 00:40:08.917
And then just as a general rule,

00:40:08.917 --> 00:40:10.957
I always do the three-click rule

00:40:10.957 --> 00:40:14.477
and then try to divide, not everything needs to be,

00:40:14.477 --> 00:40:16.957
also not everything needs to be in one dashboard.

00:40:16.957 --> 00:40:18.316
If it's different problems,

00:40:18.316 --> 00:40:21.477
you can have different pages or different dashboards.

00:40:21.477 --> 00:40:25.876
So I would, that's the approach that I've been doing.

00:40:25.876 --> 00:40:27.237
I like different dashboards.

00:40:27.237 --> 00:40:29.556
I feel like if there are more than one page of a dashboard,

00:40:29.556 --> 00:40:31.076
I will only ever look at one.

00:40:31.076 --> 00:40:33.076
I won't know the other pages exist.

00:40:33.076 --> 00:40:36.037
And anytime I've been tasked to take over a dashboard

00:40:36.037 --> 00:40:37.917
that has 16 tabs on it, I'm like,

00:40:37.917 --> 00:40:40.316
oh no, no one's clicking those other 16 tabs.

00:40:40.316 --> 00:40:42.196
Y'all, what are you doing?

00:40:42.196 --> 00:40:44.196
They're looking at one.

00:40:44.196 --> 00:40:45.357
Adam, those are great questions.

00:40:45.357 --> 00:40:47.436
Thank you so much for asking.

00:40:47.436 --> 00:40:52.076
We almost always have a career question by about this time.

00:40:52.076 --> 00:40:55.797
And I'm so glad that we ended up getting one in Slido

00:40:55.797 --> 00:40:56.957
from an anonymous asker.

00:40:56.957 --> 00:41:00.316
So I will read it and I'm gonna go ahead

00:41:00.316 --> 00:41:05.316
and put it in the chat so everybody can read it as well.

00:41:05.316 --> 00:41:07.397
And it says, a year ago,

00:41:07.397 --> 00:41:10.157
I moved up from data scientist to manager.

00:41:10.157 --> 00:41:13.237
I feel I am now no longer as close to the code

00:41:13.237 --> 00:41:14.556
as I used to be.

00:41:14.556 --> 00:41:17.357
What advice can you give me to stay up to date

00:41:17.357 --> 00:41:19.196
with data science developments?

00:41:19.196 --> 00:41:20.876
I go to presentations,

00:41:20.876 --> 00:41:23.876
but I feel I am being sold ideas

00:41:23.876 --> 00:41:26.597
that may not be realistic to implement.

00:41:26.597 --> 00:41:27.676
I love this question.

00:41:28.676 --> 00:41:30.516
Well, it's a great question.

00:41:31.477 --> 00:41:36.477
I think, yeah, I know the sentiment,

00:41:39.316 --> 00:41:42.357
but in terms of,

00:41:44.196 --> 00:41:47.196
I rarely have time for actually doing coding anymore.

00:41:47.196 --> 00:41:49.876
Every now and then I can get a burst of time

00:41:49.876 --> 00:41:51.277
to go have a little fun.

00:41:52.357 --> 00:41:54.717
How do I stay a little bit active on that?

00:41:54.717 --> 00:41:56.717
I mean, one way when I can have fun,

00:41:57.076 --> 00:41:58.436
since I don't have time to write the code,

00:41:58.436 --> 00:42:00.996
sometimes I turn to the LLM and I'll say,

00:42:00.996 --> 00:42:03.116
hey, can you go generate this?

00:42:03.116 --> 00:42:06.556
And in fact, I had a recent case where I was,

00:42:06.556 --> 00:42:09.717
this was with Posit Connect and some security issue on,

00:42:12.477 --> 00:42:13.636
yeah, you don't even wanna know,

00:42:13.636 --> 00:42:17.357
but it was on cross-site scripting.

00:42:17.357 --> 00:42:21.917
Anyway, so I actually asked the LLM to generate me

00:42:21.917 --> 00:42:24.797
a demo app to prevent cross-site scripting

00:42:24.797 --> 00:42:28.157
and this and that with secure modal dialogues

00:42:28.157 --> 00:42:30.717
and basically pop-up boxes that you see

00:42:30.717 --> 00:42:32.037
in your applications.

00:42:34.797 --> 00:42:39.436
But I asked, this is a JavaScript thing with Shiny and R,

00:42:39.436 --> 00:42:42.797
but the LLM gave me a great response and I got to go in,

00:42:42.797 --> 00:42:45.676
it wrote my code and I was able to go in and play with it

00:42:45.676 --> 00:42:48.597
and push it in, learned a whole new technique

00:42:48.597 --> 00:42:51.157
about how to use JavaScript with ShinyJS

00:42:51.157 --> 00:42:55.316
and calls to actually render a pop-up box

00:42:55.316 --> 00:42:58.357
in a quote-unquote secure way.

00:42:58.357 --> 00:43:00.917
And that was a demo I used for security

00:43:00.917 --> 00:43:03.516
to solve an issue and a question they had

00:43:03.516 --> 00:43:05.516
and then pass it on to other developers.

00:43:05.516 --> 00:43:09.636
So that's one way certainly to stay in touch.

00:43:09.636 --> 00:43:13.277
I think that AI can help you do that

00:43:13.277 --> 00:43:15.717
to remain a little closer to the coding

00:43:15.717 --> 00:43:19.917
without feeling like you don't remember

00:43:19.917 --> 00:43:21.876
all these things that you know,

00:43:21.876 --> 00:43:24.636
like trying to build an app, where do I begin?

00:43:24.636 --> 00:43:28.237
But definitely there.

00:43:28.237 --> 00:43:31.196
And then if you're a manager and you have developers,

00:43:31.196 --> 00:43:33.876
I mean, continue to stay in touch with them,

00:43:33.876 --> 00:43:38.876
ask them to, put more work on them to stay up to date

00:43:38.917 --> 00:43:40.397
and engaged with the community

00:43:40.397 --> 00:43:41.917
and schedule meetings with them

00:43:41.917 --> 00:43:44.397
and ask them what they're seeing in developments

00:43:44.397 --> 00:43:46.797
in Python or R, right?

00:43:47.237 --> 00:43:50.917
What techniques are they bringing into their development

00:43:50.917 --> 00:43:54.477
with the, and continue to participate in Posit calls

00:43:54.477 --> 00:43:58.717
and public forums or Python calls and conferences.

00:43:58.717 --> 00:44:00.876
So, and then you hear something,

00:44:00.876 --> 00:44:03.237
push it down to your team and ask them to figure it out.

00:44:03.237 --> 00:44:07.277
I think that's where as a manager, I do that all the time.

00:44:07.277 --> 00:44:08.636
So I get on with Posit.

00:44:08.636 --> 00:44:11.597
In fact, with Carlos, we had this situation

00:44:11.597 --> 00:44:13.196
where we were trying to do some massively

00:44:13.196 --> 00:44:16.717
parallel computing and the team wanted to use Spark,

00:44:17.636 --> 00:44:18.477
which is a little old,

00:44:18.477 --> 00:44:21.917
but we got on with Posit and with the solution engineer

00:44:21.917 --> 00:44:24.196
and they said, hey, have you looked into Dask?

00:44:24.196 --> 00:44:27.076
And it was a smaller group and we hadn't heard of Dask.

00:44:27.076 --> 00:44:28.717
So then, but I turned it around and said,

00:44:28.717 --> 00:44:30.277
hey guys, can y'all look into Dask,

00:44:30.277 --> 00:44:33.116
go check it out in your parallel computation architecture

00:44:33.116 --> 00:44:36.157
and bring me back a report on which works, what doesn't

00:44:36.157 --> 00:44:38.397
and see if you can get it to work.

00:44:38.397 --> 00:44:40.477
So that's the role of the manager, right?

00:44:40.477 --> 00:44:42.556
You hear something, you see something,

00:44:42.556 --> 00:44:45.196
stay up to date and then push it down

00:44:45.196 --> 00:44:47.397
and see if your team can embrace it and learn it

00:44:47.397 --> 00:44:48.676
and bring it back to you.

00:44:48.676 --> 00:44:50.797
So I hope that helps.

00:44:50.797 --> 00:44:51.636
I hope so too.

00:44:51.636 --> 00:44:52.477
I'm sure it did.

