00:47:15.436 --> 00:47:18.676
So yeah, Jason, so the question was,

00:47:20.396 --> 00:47:23.517
how would you recommend people to get domain experience

00:47:24.436 --> 00:47:27.196
without actually being part of a team

00:47:27.196 --> 00:47:29.237
working in that specific domain?

00:47:30.117 --> 00:47:33.757
For example, if I want to...

00:47:33.757 --> 00:47:37.757
So I'm currently in a financial services company

00:47:38.036 --> 00:47:40.597
as well, but I want to kind of switch

00:47:40.597 --> 00:47:43.076
towards fraud and compliance.

00:47:44.637 --> 00:47:49.637
But apart from the technical experience that I need,

00:47:50.036 --> 00:47:53.637
I'm not sure how do I gain that domain experience.

00:47:53.637 --> 00:47:56.436
So yeah, I was just wondering if you had any thoughts.

00:47:57.477 --> 00:47:59.997
Yeah, that is a complicated one

00:47:59.997 --> 00:48:02.997
because fraud is certainly an area

00:48:02.997 --> 00:48:05.556
where there's very proprietary data, right?

00:48:06.357 --> 00:48:10.276
I would recommend though that,

00:48:12.517 --> 00:48:14.837
wish I had figured working.

00:48:14.837 --> 00:48:19.837
So one thing would be to reach out to people on LinkedIn

00:48:20.916 --> 00:48:23.916
that are doing roles where you think you might wanna be

00:48:23.916 --> 00:48:26.517
and see if you can engage them or work a network

00:48:26.517 --> 00:48:27.796
to try to find someone working there

00:48:27.796 --> 00:48:30.957
and figure out what techniques are they using

00:48:30.957 --> 00:48:33.036
because different companies use different techniques.

00:48:33.156 --> 00:48:37.916
Obviously, continue to go online and look for resources

00:48:37.916 --> 00:48:41.156
and trusted resources like Data Camp

00:48:41.156 --> 00:48:43.237
probably has some tutorials.

00:48:43.237 --> 00:48:46.757
Other areas will have fraud tutorials.

00:48:46.757 --> 00:48:51.757
I think there's even one, maybe an AWS on SageMaker AI,

00:48:52.357 --> 00:48:55.517
like one of their quick start examples,

00:48:55.517 --> 00:48:57.957
they might have something on fraud

00:48:57.957 --> 00:49:00.957
that you can try on an email basis.

00:49:00.997 --> 00:49:03.796
And I don't remember if that's probit or logit

00:49:03.796 --> 00:49:06.237
or LPMs or whatever they're doing,

00:49:06.237 --> 00:49:10.396
but or if it's just complete email with fine tuning.

00:49:13.196 --> 00:49:16.997
But like gradient boosting models and that sort of stuff.

00:49:16.997 --> 00:49:21.357
So I would look toward those particular demos

00:49:21.357 --> 00:49:24.757
and use cases and try to learn that.

00:49:24.757 --> 00:49:27.117
I mean, use the LLMs too to help you out,

00:49:27.117 --> 00:49:30.837
perplexity computer, I love perplexity.

00:49:31.676 --> 00:49:33.717
Tell it what you wanna do, how to get domain experience.

00:49:33.717 --> 00:49:37.117
The one thing I find exciting that LLMs can do pretty well

00:49:37.117 --> 00:49:40.556
is ask it to generate a synthetic dataset for you

00:49:40.556 --> 00:49:43.676
and then test your code on a synthetic dataset, right?

00:49:43.676 --> 00:49:47.597
So you could try to get like a real world example that way.

00:49:47.597 --> 00:49:50.676
There are tools too to help you create synthetic datasets

00:49:50.676 --> 00:49:52.357
for your objectives.

00:49:52.357 --> 00:49:55.276
So that way you're getting some domain experiences

00:49:55.276 --> 00:49:57.837
with synthetic data, so.

00:49:57.837 --> 00:49:59.316
Yes, I love it.

00:49:59.316 --> 00:50:00.237
I have some advice.

00:50:00.637 --> 00:50:01.637
I know we have three minutes left,

00:50:01.637 --> 00:50:05.076
but if you already work in a big company,

00:50:05.076 --> 00:50:07.517
find out if you have a fraud department

00:50:07.517 --> 00:50:09.597
and then go express interest in cross-training,

00:50:09.597 --> 00:50:11.637
ask questions, find out what kind of fraud

00:50:11.637 --> 00:50:13.477
your company is trying to battle

00:50:13.477 --> 00:50:17.117
and then go meet as many fraud workers as you can

00:50:17.117 --> 00:50:18.036
and find out what they do,

00:50:18.036 --> 00:50:20.637
because there's like 50,000 different flavors of fraud.

00:50:20.637 --> 00:50:22.237
I worked in debit card fraud,

00:50:22.237 --> 00:50:24.517
which was very different from the type of fraud

00:50:24.517 --> 00:50:26.676
that somebody else might see.

00:50:27.517 --> 00:50:30.076
And once you understand how that fraud happens

00:50:30.916 --> 00:50:33.237
and how it needs to be handled,

00:50:33.237 --> 00:50:36.196
you can start to develop those synthetic datasets

00:50:36.196 --> 00:50:39.556
more easily yourself with fake transaction data

00:50:39.556 --> 00:50:40.556
